2026-06-24 16:03:14,468 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Starship R&D as a Percentage of FY2025 Denominators\n\n### Inputs (FY2025, from the SpaceX S-1 filed May 20, 2026)\n\nAll figures reflect the retrospectively recast consolidated entity (SpaceX + xAI + X Holdings) under common-control accounting.\n\n| Metric | FY2025 Value |\n|---|---|\n| Starship R&D expense (Space segment) | $3,004 million |\n| Space segment revenue | $4,086 million |\n| Space segment Segment Adjusted EBITDA | $653 million |\n| Consolidated total revenue | $18,674 million |\n\nThe S-1 explicitly states: "In 2025, our Space segment generated a loss from operations of $(657) million and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $653 million, including the impact of funding $3,004 million in research and development expense for our next-generation Starship launch vehicle program."\n\n### Calculations\n\n1. **Starship R&D ÷ Space segment revenue**\n   = $3,004M ÷ $4,086M = **73.52%**\n\n2. **Starship R&D ÷ Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA**\n   = $3,004M ÷ $653M = **460.03%** (i.e., Starship R&D is ~4.6x Space segment Adjusted EBITDA)\n\n3. **Starship R&D ÷ Consolidated revenue**\n   = $3,004M ÷ $18,674M = **16.09%**\n\n### Which Denominator Is Most Informative?\n\n**Space segment revenue (73.52%) is the most informative denominator for assessing the development burden of Starship.**\n\nReasoning:\n\n- **It isolates the segment that actually bears the cost.** Starship R&D is incurred entirely within the Space segment. Dividing by Space segment revenue directly measures how much of the segment\'s top line is being consumed by next-generation vehicle development — a clean "R&D intensity" metric for the business unit funding the program. Consolidated revenue dilutes this signal by including Connectivity ($11,387M) and AI ($3,201M) revenue, which have no economic relationship to Starship spending.\n\n- **Segment Adjusted EBITDA (460%) is distorted and not a useful burden metric.** Segment Adjusted EBITDA is *already net of* the Starship R&D expense (it is derived from a $(657)M operating loss, then add-backed for D&A, SBC, and impairments — but R&D is left in). Using it as a denominator therefore double-counts the very cost being measured: the more SpaceX spends on Starship, the smaller the denominator gets, mechanically inflating the ratio. A ratio above 100% (here, ~460%) is mathematically valid but economically misleading because it conflates the cause (Starship spend) with the effect (compressed segment profitability). It tells you Starship is large relative to *post-Starship* segment cash earnings, but it does not cleanly measure "burden."\n\n- **Consolidated revenue (16.09%) understates the burden.** Because the recast entity folds in xAI and X Holdings, consolidated revenue is roughly 4.6x Space segment revenue. The 16% figure makes Starship look like a modest corporate R&D line item when, within the segment that funds it, it consumes nearly three-quarters of revenue. This denominator is useful only for cross-company R&D-intensity benchmarking (e.g., versus other large-cap tech/defense peers), not for evaluating the development burden on the launch business itself.\n\n**Conclusion:** Space segment revenue (73.52%) is the most informative denominator. It is the only one of the three that (i) is economically tied to the cost being measured, (ii) is not itself reduced by the cost (unlike Segment Adjusted EBITDA), and (iii) is not diluted by unrelated businesses (unlike consolidated revenue). It shows that Starship development consumed roughly three-quarters of the Space segment\'s FY2025 revenue — a striking illustration of the development burden that the consolidated and EBITDA-based ratios obscure.\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Financial Highlights, Accelerating Investment in Growth and Innovation, and Capital Allocation sections; Segment reconciliation table"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
